pr_body:
Adds two rules for `cargo`:

- `cargo`: for those who are too used to simply type `make` and are fucked every time they want `cargo` to actually compile their project;
- `cargo_no_command`: fixes spelling mistakes, similar to the `git_not_command` rule.

Fixes #1011 

This PR allows the user to span ForeignKey relationships with AutoSlugField's `populate_from` argument. It also allows the user use model methods in the `populate_from` argument. 

@trbs please let me know any feedback or suggestions? Thanks again for your work on this library, and for considering this PR!

A proposal on how to merge widgets together when they take multiple input types and how to separate out their handlers. This proposal uses a mixin and decorators to register different handler types to individual classes. While the implementation covers only `Orange.data.Table` type inputs, this will be expanded to all input types, so it will be able to be used in any widget that will need to handle multiple input types.
A toy example on how using the mixin should look:

```python
class Widget(MultiInputMixin):
    my_property = 1
    attribute = 'none'

    def set_data(self, data):
        pass

    def dummy_method(self):
        pass


@Widget.data_handler(target_type=InputTypes.DISCRETE)
class Discrete:
    attribute = 'discrete'

    def simple_method(self, *args):
        pass


@Widget.data_handler(target_type=InputTypes.CONTINUOUS)
class Continuous:
    attribute = 'continuous'

    def simple_method(self, *args):
        pass

```

A full example can be seen [here](https://github.com/pavlin-policar/orange3-prototypes/blob/cr-merge-widgets/orangecontrib/prototypes/widgets/owknn.py#L15-L76).


Pros:
 - All the methods and properties that handle a single input type are grouped together in the same class, which should make understanding and debugging fairly simple.
 - The very minimal API should make converting existing widgets that are separated to a single widget fairly simple.

Cons:
 - Pylint will undoubtedly complain in the handler classes since handlers will probably need to access properties of the base class, but since the handler methods are bound to the base class at runtime, they technically don't exist in the handler, hence the errors.

The implementation is not yet functional on orange widgets, there are still several issues I need to work out, but any comments or suggestions on the API would help a great deal.

